- http://logs.openstack.org/00/39100/1/check/gate-grenade-devstack-vm/22418 : SUCCESS in 42m 14s
'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2013-07-30 00:23:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

It's also not clear to me that you want to leave the package repo in a broken state like this, as lots of other tools will break later."}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-07-30 06:13:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Would you pref a fix be to remove the uninstall and leave it with the package manager thinking that they are installed - even if they have the wrong version because pip install will replace them?

Removing these packages - specifically python-lxml - breaks xenserver-core because yum forcibly removes that too.

Clearly it's only luck that I saw this, and removing these packages at all could cause any number of 'breakages' on the users system by rermoving packages that are expected to be kept without them knowing."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-07-30 15:41:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sigh.  RHEL Python config bites again.

How do you handle this in a production installation?  We already require EPEL and RDO for a RHEL installation, can you find appropriate packages in either of those repos?

The idea of upgrading a library underneath something else doesn't sit well with me.  Doesn't that also affect vendor supportability requirements?"}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-07-31 12:48:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I agree - I guess that production installs are fine because they just use the distro's packages and don't need to track lxml or crypto more closely like we do in devstack for gating.

EPEL doesn't appear to have a newer version of python-lxml (so if the cinder/nova requirements really are for >=2.3 then the 2.2 isn't high enough) - but I assumed that the primary reason we're removing it is so we can rely on updating the requirements.txt files ourselves and automatically updating?"}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-07-31 12:51:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

http://repos.fedorapeople.org/repos/openstack/openstack-trunk/ is where I looked for the EPEL/RDO RPMs btw - so it seems as though RDO uses an older version of python-lxml than we "require"!'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2013-08-01 06:12:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'm not sure this is a good idea; it leaves the package manager in a bit of a weird state.

Do you require the removed packages?  The bug doesn't explain what the problem is."}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-08-01 08:54:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

We've agreed that this probably isn't the right fix - but I was leaving this open to get more input on the right way.

I know that removing python-lxml forceably removes Xen - but this is a generic issue and devstack shouldn't be removing packages and potentially breaking someone's system by also removing the dependencies."}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2013-08-01 09:52:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The issue for removing them is (as hopefully explained in the comments) that pip-python on RHEL wants to install any "aftermarket" packages right over the top of the existing ones, rather than putting them in /usr/local etc.  Otherwise you could just pip install libxml and the rpm version would be ignored by python.

The idea of an isolation method isolation method like virtualenv or --user (although [1] makes this hard) seems complex.

Can we have a devstack-rpm repo where we keep some more modern versions around?  Apart from the maintenance version, that seems like the most straight forward solution?

[1] https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=961546'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2013-08-02 05:48:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

> I know that removing python-lxml forceably removes Xen

Will [1] satisfy this?  By having a dummy python-lxml package installed xen should remain happy; presumably backwards compatibility is such that it will work fine with the version installed from pip.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/39862/'}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-08-03 18:55:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

Agreed with Ian - I think that his patch is significantly safer, so would prefer to see that move forward rather than this one.'}]

commit_message:
Remove status* fields from HealthMonitor model

Status and status_description fields of HealthMonitor
model are never changed during lifetime of the object
and doesn't represent the status of it's pysical
implementation. Instead, status and status_description
of PoolMonitorAssociation is used. Another reason for
removing those fields is that HealthMonitor acts as
template which is instantiated on device. Status field
for template makes no sense.

fixes bug 1207650

Change-Id: Iea9d7f73c3a2db43c553ed06a64fe5ff42427167

commit_message:
Fix enum definition in FWaaS DB schema migration

Applying of migration 39cf3f799352 fails due to the error
in definiton of action Enum type (values are not passed).

Fixes bug 1207805

commit_message:
Code dedup in class QuotaReserveSqlAlchemyTestCase

Moved common parts to setUp()
   -quotas
   -deltas
   -usages
Move reservations update and usages init to separate functions

bp nova-tests-code-duplication

commit_message:
Refactor EC2 API error handling code

Implements blueprint ec2-error-codes

Redundant logging code was united in new __init__.py:ec2_error_ex() helper
function and all standard EC2 error responses are now uniformly logged on
DEBUG log level because they are just responses to invalid client requests,
not nova errors.  Unexpected client/server errors are logged on ERROR/CRITICAL
level and their exception name is used as error code - no more useless
UnknownError. Error descriptions are supressed for unexpected server errors as
they might contain sensitive information. New unit tests are provided.

The code for consturcting EC2 error response which was duplicated in
__init__.py:ec2_error and faults.py:Fault was moved to
faults.py:ec2_error_response.

__init__.py:exception_to_ec2code helper function now always returns exception
name as an EC2 error code since there are no exceptions with ec2_code
attribute yet. These will be added in the follwing patch as required by
referenced blueprint.

This code cleanup serves as a base for future fix of current terrible EC2
error behavior.

Change-Id: Ie88b089dfe536a56f5a46e9c92ff90c6a1fef793

commit_message:
python3: Fix unicode and gettext

In Python 2, ensure that the _() that gets installed into built-ins
always returns unicodes.  This matches the default behavior under Python
3, although that keyword argument is not present in the Python 3 API.

Change-Id: If9e7bb07f389149b3dcf4314f6b2b4faf2b659d0
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
Better sorting of flavors in the "Launch Instance" view

By default, returns the available flavors, sorted by RAM usage
(ascending).  Override these behaviours with a CREATE_INSTANCE_FLAVOR_SORT
dict in local_settings.py.

DocImpact: a new django setting, CREATE_INSTANCE_FLAVOR_SORT.

Change-Id: I9f466ff306739369a85f7176da27932958fc8867
Fixes: Bug 1196690

commit_message:
Cleanup copy/paste in test_quota_sets

Tests in test_quota_sets extensively use quota_set data that's
copy/pasted everywhere, so introduce a method that generates this
quota_set data and make use of it in the tests.

blueprint nova-tests-code-duplication

Change-Id: Icac3e4b5f48592c63a8376c84a744f3dac0cec36

commit_message:
Close object-server connection as soon as possible

close_swift_conn will close the connection with the object-server straight
away instead of reading the response (and thus wasting resources, see
bug report).

On the object server the DiskFile will catch the GeneratorExit/Timeout
exception logging that the client was disconnected on read and
flushing the buffer cache for the open file. Finally the file is closed.

Change-Id: I49977ea08b1532b92885f39971e3c2d15d2b46d1
Fixes: bug #1174660

commit_message:
Enable Heat and Neutron and Horizon service

Configure tempest to test Neutron and Heat and Horizon services
when it is an enabled devstack service or when it explicitly stated as enabled
service in the localrc.

Using list=true will cause IndexError because the arg_value don't
handle the empty situation. This Commit Fix this problem and enable

Fixes: Bug #1108365

commit_message:
Enable create port with argument list=true

Currently, we can specify security-groups with duplicate option
--security-group sgid1 --security-group sgid2.
Using list=true will cause IndexError because the arg_value don't
handle the empty situation. This Commit Fix this problem and enable
the following style:
--security-groups list=true sgid1 sgid2

Change-Id: Ia2896666973496770133b7a0b76ad7a71ce970c3
Fixes: Bug #1108365

subject: Manager layer caching
messages:
[{'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-07-26 20:10:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Work In Progress

the goal of this review is just to illustrate this approach to using memcached/redis as a cache, regardless of which backend is configured for a particular driver interface. so you can use the sql token driver and the ldap identity driver, but still cache calls to both in memcached.

the functional test suite currently expect zero caching behavior, which i think is fine, but we should deploy in devstack with some small caching duration (1-15 seconds?).

removing kwargs from manager calls needs to be moved into it's own patch and the revised keystone.conf is far from being able to expose the full configurability of dogpile.cache"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-26 21:12:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Doesn't seem to work

"}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2013-07-27 00:36:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

At a quick glance, this makes sense and there is the concern on how to handle invalidation.  I'll need to look closer at how CONF works, but I think you are correct in that we can't utilize it from the point that the region is currently being built from.

WRT - functional test suite, I'd like to get some simple cache (contrived) tests in place where we have a test that makes a request, changes the underlying value, checks that the change hasn't taken, sleeps for a short bit and then checks that the new value is in place.  This would be only a contrived call that is used for testing to ensure we don't miss something if say the dogpile.cache changes... or worse someone breaks the configuration.  (I'll see what i can brew up here).

In devstack, it makes a lot of sense to incorporate the short cache you've outlined, and I see this as something that should be verified works as expected via tempest (eventually).

The way I see this working is moving the kwargs from the manager calls probably should come before the caching, with the cache dependant on that change.  Expanding keystone.conf to handle the corpus of dogpile.cache's configuration will be a bit more work.  I would also lean towards making the in-memory cache the default (since it doesn't impact results with HTTPD like KVS systems do, being only a cache).  

I'll do some work on this and see what I can come up with in addition to whats here already."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-03 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

code review expired after 1 week of no activity after a negative review, it can be restored using the `Restore Change` button under the Patch Set on the web interface'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-03 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Make pending_timeout an argument of __init__

Just like stale_reads_ok, this was already an argument, end even
used by the replicator that way. We only make it used exclusively
this way, so that we can document it for LFS.

Change-Id: Ib722093a476ec75d87917b37b40b77dcf2627330

[{'created': '2013-08-03 00:09:23.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Add evaluation of --force parameter when creating snapshots"

This reverts commit 854740c4c793444c955180e7c0c96977e3e06c56

What we should've caught here is that the args actually passes in a Bool, which then fails the .lower().

Also, if we want to do things like check for strings representing bools we should use the utils.bool_from_str() method rather than write it inline like this.'}]
commit_message:
Revert "Add evaluation of --force parameter when creating snapshots"

This reverts commit 854740c4c793444c955180e7c0c96977e3e06c56

What we should've caught here is that the args actually passes in a Bool, which then fails the .lower().

Also, if we want to do things like check for strings representing bools we should use the utils.bool_from_str() method rather than write it inline like this.

'}, {'account_id': 1030, 'date': '2013-07-26 18:10:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 18: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

1 bug inline.  But I've been thinking about this a little more.  What you have is very close to correct.  But I think there's a change in behavior under this condition:

cell_name in API cell exists, but no 'host' is set yet.  In this case, there's not going to be any message to cells at all to delete the instance in the child cell.  Your code in cells_api will super()... and the super() will just run _local_delete() which has no cast in it.

So, there's a couple of options:  You could revert most of the changes in cells_api.py but call the new cells methods instead of the run_compute_api_method.  Or we could mix in the cells support in api.py completely.

I think my preference is to just do the former for now and we do the integration later?  If you revert most of the cells stuff, you can ditch the cells decorators in api.py also."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-07-26 23:56:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 19.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-27 01:12:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 19: Doesn't seem to work

I had a long review comment in patch set 18 that i'll re-post here because i don't see it addressed yet or any reply:

I've been thinking about this a little more. What you have is very close to correct.  But I think there's a change in behavior under this condition:
cell_name in API cell exists, but no 'host' is set yet. In this case, there's not going to be any message to cells at all to delete the instance in the child cell. Your code in cells_api will super()... and the super() will just run _local_delete() which has no cast in it.

So, there's a couple of options: You could revert most of the changes in cells_api.py but call the new cells methods instead of the run_compute_api_method. Or we could mix in the cells support in api.py completely.

I think my preference is to just do the former for now and we do the integration later? If you revert most of the cells stuff, you can ditch the cells decorators in api.py also."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-07-30 18:04:50.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 20.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-07-30 18:06:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 20: Do not merge

Update API documentation

commit_message:
Add Pagination of collections across the API

Pagination is designed to return a subset of the larger collection while
providing a link that can be used to retrieve the next. The next link
will preserve any parameters sent in the initial request.

The patch also creates a new 'api' option group and move the existing
api configuration from the [default] section to the new [api] section.

Implements blueprint add-api-pagination

Change-Id: I3e72599344b7716a3ac88e504d018cbe7b0764b3

commit_message:
Add an exclusion for projects not on pbr

If a project isn't on pbr, then force-upgrading their setup.py will
be a categorical disaster.

Once glance and swift have finished moving, we can remove this 'feature'
but for now, it's a blocker.

Change-Id: I6ab41be97a2ff83c395861a95244d090c543d1fb

commit_message:
Add evaluation of --force parameter when creating snapshots

Raise BadRequest Exception if value of --force parameter in
snapshot-create is invalid

Fixes: bug #1014689

Change-Id: If4858dc17cedf027112defb935016137727681cc

commit_message:
Use oslo.sphinx and remove local copy of doc theme

Use the new oslo.sphinx version of the OpenStack doc
theme instead of copying it into this repo.

blueprint oslo.sphinx

Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug.hellmann@dreamhost.com>

commit_message:
Modify authenticate_user to authenticate in Driver

Commit 661cef927e95cf87a96eea7f0f6d840f8bf4adcd forgot to modify
function name from "authenticate_user" to "authenticate" in
identity.core.Driver as same as its implementation in backends.

Fixes bug #1205516

Change-Id: I650d191778b2b8fbd93a0c3f093ba6b5cc88b81f

commit_message:
python3: Fix python3 tox installation

Fix python3 tox installation so that it uses setuptools
by default rather than use distribute.

Also bump the version used by teestrepository so that
it uses a more python3 compliant version.

Change-Id: If2522f12889e66cedc6286d48ba8105c685e6e0e
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
Enable zero the snapshot when delete snapshot in LVMVolumeDriver

Because snapshot without 'size' field, So clear_volume method in
LVMVolumeDriver will skip secure deleting. Get the size of snapshot from
'volume_size' filed, So it can zero the snapshot.

Remove the 'size_in_g' parameter in _delete_volume method, because it never
used. Add a unittest for clear_volume method.

Fixes  Bug #1198185

Change-Id: Ie919b50ce4fb276f29ab2e0279f868a691ea7bef
(cherry picked from commit 0ee31073c5cb432a9cdd2648e99aa802b0ed0a17)

commit_message:
Stub out dependency on subprocess in unit tests

Stub out the sheepdog Store dependency on subprocess communication
with collie.  This results in many unnecessary pipes being created
on POSIX systems.

For unit testing purposes, do not create the sheepdog store.  (There
are no unit tests for this functionality anyway.)

Change-Id: I54014a502891ae52bb567f3fae32e6ff0c74332a

commit_message:
Add a more complicated graph example.

Add an example that creates tasks that will
build a car and has the dependencies specified
to build the car in the right order and have each
task be submitted to the flow and then run and
watch the tasks occur in the right order automatically.

Change-Id: I17a2f621dfd7ceefb0a9c863e3e68b21b92672c2

commit_message:
Add a new simple calculator example.

Add a simple linear calculator example which will
be given a few sets of tasks to do and some initial provided
data and then combine the correct ordering of that tasks
to produce an output result that then can be extracted.

Change-Id: Ica84dff67ce0a6b7699cd98effebc85c7dbd4cb2

commit_message:
Deep-copy not always possible.

In working with cinder it appears that at last
cinder is using objects which can not be deep
copied (sqlalchemy objects) and which actually
cause the deepcopy routine to fail. To get
around this avoid the deepcopy until proven
its really needed.

Change-Id: Ia7b7c49e82c2151351cc0f78ecb1531c35540652

Setup test volume fails without lvm2

On Ubuntu, the lvm2 package isn't installed by default.
Setup test volume fails without the lvm2 package installed first.

Change-Id: I1c453102d3554fd4853e626af5daa74367ced88b

commit_message:
Support programmatic use of disk config extension

Allow servers to be created, resized, and rebuilt with the disk_config
option:

http://api.openstack.org/api-ref.html#ext-os-disk-config

There is a separate extension that exists for disk config already, but
it only works via the novaclient CLI interface, not via programmatic use
of python-novaclient as a library.

assert changes in tests/v1_1/fakes allow for other data in rebuild
and resize requests.

Change-Id: I8051ffb8747cf5c67b0199d22fbbe80306b01499

commit_message:
Fix multi availability zone issue part 1

Current aggregate APIs allow user to add multi
AZs to a host, but Openstack support single AZ
of a host. When booting an instance, nova uses
the first AZ assigned to a host,even if user
assigned multi AZs to the host and user chose
the second AZ to boot an instance. So multi AZs
aren't supported by current Openstack design,
we should fix aggregate APIs to align the design
. This patch is for limit user to add multi AZs
using aggregate-add-host API.

The part 2 limits user to add multi AZs using aggregate
update and aggregate metadata update API, here is the
link:
I18ad1ac22c6aee298ccc75c978b85241ae1ac616

Fixes: bug #1196893

Change-Id: I788782a9f21ec2672551f75123753175bb268586

commit_message:
python3: Use six.moves for ConfigParser

Python 3 reorganized the standard library and moved several functions to different modules.
Six provides a consistent interface to them through the fake six.moves module.

Use six where necessary.

Change-Id: I996ab00d2d78fe909815712a675bb6df45a8f0d5
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
Add a example which simulates booting a vm

Show how a booting a vm like workflow could be
structured via an example and add some simple
reverting methods which will attempt to undo
the changes that they applied (automatically).

This flow is similar to how nova runs in a way.

Change-Id: Id068ef80d7702b9b5f9af3c2569b52de3c58d32d

Extract configs-related code to the configs helper

* two helpers has been added for getting single and multiple values;
* several simple tests has been added to check helpers.

commit_message:
Move examples under the source tree.

The examples will likely be easier to find
if they are colocated next to the rest of
the source tree. They can also be turned into
test cases in the future this way also.

commit_message:
Remove kwargs from manager calls where not needed.

This patch removes the use of kwargs from manager calls where not
required. Dogpile.cache (the targeted caching library) does not
support kwargs out of the box with its cache-key-generator. This
change allows us to support the default cache-key-generator; while
it is possible to create a new cache-key-generator function, there
are many possible edge-cases to deal with when making cache
invalidation calls (ensuring the arguments are the same) as well as
possible performance implications (depending on the depth of method
introspection needed to determine how to invalidate the cache).

As an added bonus, this change brings the code touched more in-line
with the rest of keystone where most manager/driver calls do not
use kwargs unless absolutley required.

blueprint: caching-layer-for-driver-calls
Change-Id: I035c976314fb48f657661f681f7c1760d3c547a6

commit_message:
xenapi: Rename imageupload image

The imageupload driver concept has helped detangle some of the image managment
code in vm_utils.

It would be nice to extend that benefit to download as well, with an
additional benefit of being able to share more code between the upload and
download paths.

This is the first in a series of patches that aims to to do just that. The
first step is change the name so that it's not just 'imageupload' but
'image'es in general that the driver is managing.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ia18b82568147a9a40b0da67d74bf20b12d08b9a9

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-02 19:44:46.000000000', 'message': 'Improve snmpd element.

The purpose of this patch is to improve the ability to monitor hosts,
correct an error in the current snmpd.conf, and align variable names
with their function.

Renames the Heat variable name prefix from "snmp" to "snmpd" in order to
align the Heat variable name with the element name.

Changes the Heat variable MIB to export_MIB to better represent what
the variable is used for.

Removes a hardcoded user name in snmpd.conf for the rouser to fix
an authentication issue for user names other then "authOnlyUser".

Creates "OoOEnabled" and "CheckProcOpenFiles" as SNMP extended
commands. The OoOEnabled command will allow elements like Nagios
to poll hosts with this element via SNMP, and receive a consistent
response. While the CheckProcOpenFiles command is a simple Nagios
style check of open files per process that will be monitored so
that an alert can be sent if any one process exceeds its open
file limit.

Change-Id: I92afd1f81dfc47c3bb0f4bb3a5aa72bee8870f48
Authored-by: Chris Krelle <nobodycam@gmail.com>
'}, {'created': '2013-08-02 19:44:46.000000000', 'message': 'Improve snmpd element.

commit_message:
Improve snmpd element.

The purpose of this patch is to improve the ability to monitor hosts,
correct an error in the current snmpd.conf, and align variable names
with their function.

Renames the Heat variable name prefix from "snmp" to "snmpd" in order to
align the Heat variable name with the element name.

Changes the Heat variable MIB to export_MIB to better represent what
the variable is used for.

Removes a hardcoded user name in snmpd.conf for the rouser to fix
an authentication issue for user names other then "authOnlyUser".

The OoOEnabled command will allow elements like Nagios to poll
hosts with this element via SNMP, and receive a consistent
response.

The CheckProcOpenFiles command is a simple Nagios style check of
open files per process that will be monitored so that an alert can
be sent if any one process exceeds its open file limit.

Change-Id: I92afd1f81dfc47c3bb0f4bb3a5aa72bee8870f48
Authored-by: Chris Krelle <nobodycam@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Clean up use of token_provider manager in tests

With 19081b834991d263d84c761dcf422a8c9faf40a1, the token_provider
is created in load_backends() so it doesn't have to be created by
the tests.

This makes the tests using token_provider_api consistent with how
other backends are used in the tests.

This change only affects unit tests.

Change-Id: I9c05c7876bd14fb28e77fe1e49dd509a2a1cb788

Any big patch that includes a major refactoring like this, should go through the steps of discussion, blue-prints & smaller patches, so that our current work is not jeopardized"}, {'account_id': 6944, 'date': '2013-08-02 15:41:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-02 16:18:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Works for me

This changes too much all at once, and replaces a form of testing instead of adding another form. After much deliberation, I've realized this patch would have made more sense as a separate test category, e.g., API or something like that. (tests/api). The needs addressed by this test are different than the needs addressed by user-oriented testing, as exists in our system/functional suite at the moment.

There are ideas in here that can be reused later. For example:

- setUpClass/tearDownClass
    * auth only once per suite
- TestHTTPClient
- decorators for each resource type
    * automatic cleanup
- header management as done by TestHTTPClient

They will continue to exist in my github branch as cabrera/marconi:fix_system_tests

Let's continue improving marconi. There's more debates to be had in the future, and I hope to learn from them. :)"}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2013-07-30 20:36:55.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor system tests, update for metadata endpnt

Rationale:

This patchset aims to make it far easier to add new system tests in
the future, and also includes support for running tests in parallel,
if a test runner supports that feature.

Some major additions include:

- Auth once per test suite:
    * Facilitated by new TestHTTPClient
- Automatic tearDown
- Automatic setUp
- Perfect clean-up by using context managers for messages, claims, and
  queues
- Some restructuring of QueueTests: QueueCreate, QueueMeta, QueueList
- Updates to queue tests to handle metadata endpoint

One new dependency is added: yurl (see: pypy - yurl). Used to simplify
URL location parsing for messages.

Also removed were various print statements and exception-handling.

One minor fix:

import configparser handled in a py3k friendly way

Change-Id: I3720ceeeb2738dea017e7a09a8912a3116ad22e0
'}, {'created': '2013-07-30 21:47:05.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor system tests, update for metadata endpnt

Rationale:

The previous mode of running tests depended on a test runner to
lexicographically sort tests by name to work correctly. That could
prove problematic if we wanted to run only a subset of tests or run
the tests in parallel.

Furthermore, clean up was not performed on test resources. As a
result, the tests were not idempotent. It was difficult to be certain
that running the tests twice would not introduce some subtle
dependency and alter the overall outcome.

commit_message:
Refactor system tests, update for metadata endpnt

Rationale:

The previous mode of running tests depended on a test runner to
lexicographically sort tests by name to work correctly. That could
prove problematic if we wanted to run only a subset of tests or run
the tests in parallel.

Furthermore, clean up was not performed on test resources. As a
result, the tests were not idempotent. It was difficult to be certain
that running the tests twice would not introduce some subtle
dependency and alter the overall outcome.

This patchset addresses these issues primarily, as well as code
DRYness.

Method:

This patchset aims to make it far easier to add new system tests in
the future, and also includes support for running tests in parallel,
if a test runner supports that feature.

Some major additions include:

- Auth once per test suite:
    * Facilitated by new TestHTTPClient
- Automatic tearDown
- Automatic setUp
- Perfect clean-up by using context managers for messages, claims, and
  queues
- Some restructuring of QueueTests: QueueCreate, QueueMeta, QueueList
- Updates to queue tests to handle metadata endpoint

One new dependency is added: yurl (see: pypy - yurl). Used to simplify
URL location parsing for messages.

Also removed were various print statements and exception-handling.

One minor fix:

import configparser handled in a py3k friendly way

Change-Id: I3720ceeeb2738dea017e7a09a8912a3116ad22e0
Implements: blueprint refactor-system-tests

commit_message:
Added headers argument support to get_object()

With this change conditional and range GETs are possible, as
documented in official API guide:
http://docs.openstack.org/api/openstack-object-storage/1.0/content/retrieve-object.html

Change-Id: Ib2ed1c21e8d3f1ed79c0b7e542ee022ee535835c

It looks like someone went out of their way to enable debug mode in sqlalchemy.  Turning on db debugging was clearly not just a side effect of some other intention, it appears to have been quite deliberate.  Are we sure we want to disable this entirely?  Can you arrange it so db debug messages is a specific conf setting?  Or perhaps have them go to a different file?  Leaking of PWs is obviously a big problem that should be solved but maybe there is another way.

note that I am not opposed to doing this, but I think we need to explicitly address whatever the historical reason was for enabling this."}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2013-07-15 20:46:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/863/

and has just been updated and carried around since then. It looks like the original intent was to ensure that connection and import errors were being shown.(turning debug for this is like going at the problem with a hammer though) Which I don't think will be a problem any more since the db code has matured quite a bit since then."}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2013-07-15 21:02:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Thanks Mathew for inclusion of the 'sqlalchemy_debug' conf property. This would be of great help.

The below points are for your consideration. Thought, if they could be included as part of this check-in it would be great. 
#1:
From the SQLAlchemy documentation, these are some minor details I could extract out:

Setting log level to,
WARN: no log operation occurs. (this is the log level that is set as default)
		eg., logging.getLogger('sqlalchemy.engine').setLevel(logging.WARN)
INFO: logs all SQL statements + repr() of their parameter list.
		eg., logging.getLogger('sqlalchemy.engine').setLevel(logging.INFO)
DEBUG: logs all SQL statements + parameter list + result rows
		eg., logging.getLogger('sqlalchemy.engine').setLevel(logging.DEBUG)

I think most of the times what we want was log at INFO level during development. Generally we might not want to log all the result rows which makes the logs very exhaustive.

If we make CONF.sqlalchemy_debug to have values either as DEBUG|INFO|WARN as part of this check-in that would be a big plus.
	eg., sqlalchemy_debug = False (means set to WARN)
		 sqlalchemy_debug = True (means set log level to INFO) 		
		 sqlalchemy_debug = 'debug' (means set log level to DEBUG)
This is the same way how sqlalchemy's keyword parameter, 'echo' is set while invoking create_engine().

#2:
If we could change the name of the CONF property from 'sqlalchemy_debug' to some thing like 'sql_connection_debug' or 'connection_debug' as defined in nova, it would sound consistent with rest of the properties used for SQLAlchemy from both glance-api.conf & glance-registry.conf."}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2013-07-23 17:57:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2013-07-23 17:57:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Turn off debug logging in sqlalchemy by default

This commit adds a new config option sqlalchemy_debug which is used
for enabling debug messages from sqlalchemy. Previously, this logging
was enabled whenever debug was enabled. The debug log level for
sqlalchemy prints out all SQL queries and results which is way too
verbose for most cases where just debug logging is useful. This
change disables this previous behavior by defaulting the new option
to false and decoupling it from the debug config option.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I298c40b71ed0b8772ff956f61f8d94217bce0e11

commit_message:
Python Savanna Client initial implementation

Image Registry:
* Register Images and Tags
* Edit existing Images and Tags
* Unregister Images

Supports create, read and delete operations for:
* Node Group Templates
* Cluster Templates
* Clusters

No CLI support

Implements blueprint python-savannaclient

Change-Id: If0b7c4fb9660d646cb37c4b224bdcf39dc61bb19

commit_message:
Reset migrating task state for MigrationError exceptions

Create an exception type for pre-check errors and add it to the list
of exceptions for which instance task state is reset to ACTIVE to
avoid cases where an instance get stuck in MIGRATING state.

Convert existing instances of raise MigrationError in scheduler and
driver pre-checks to have them raise the new MigrationPreCheckError
exception instead.

In addition, also make sure that expected exceptions are passed over
RPC silently.

Resolves bug 1171526.

Conflicts:
	nova/scheduler/filter_scheduler.py
	nova/scheduler/manager.py
	nova/virt/xenapi/vmops.py

Change-Id: I00fa0962e555f895dd98861684ec7767fed3b37b
(cherry picked from commit 9eb3dc7ed44d99652a17238724842e3067d46120)

commit_message:
Ec2Signer : Allow signature verification for older boto versions

Since the fix for bug #1197553, verification for older clients (which strip the
port when formatting the request) fails.

This conditionally reverts to the original behavior, by detecting the boto
version via the User-Agent header, the default behavior will be the new
behavior (which doesn't strip the port), but this will allow a less painful
transition for clients/distros to the new boto version.

Fixes bug #1205281

Change-Id: I54ac9c5ba91e697004f1346a8f2d685da488992a

commit_message:
xenapi: refactor spawn to prep for more code share

To fix a bug related to inconsistent behavior between spawn and
finish_migration, I have refactored the spawn code so it will be easier
to share with finish_migration.

Mostly the refactor is to make the spawn steps more granular calls that
can more easily be shared with the finish_migration.

As part of this change I have slightly changed the grouping of the
operations into the steps that report progress, so the progress changes
are more meaningful.

Change-Id: Ied7a67825bd02953544fb50fc5a24d64a92901d9

commit_message:
Update update.py to also write a stock setup.py

One of the points of pbr was ensuring that we had a consistent build
environment, but we still have boilerplate setup.py laying around.
Install the right boilerplate at update time.

Change-Id: If4b2e16b469171204270ace8144792e607cfddd7

commit_message:
Add quantum/neutron support to openstack-compute

This commit introduces a new node attribute which will
turn off nova-networking and enable quantum/neutron
style networking and install the appropriate dependant
packages.

Change-Id: Ia9dadf736e6e916f4b25c202cb88cb8a030d54c0

commit_message:
Refactor compute API's delete to properly do local soft_deletes

Right now, if you try to soft_delete something that is on a downed
host, the _local_delete code will actually hard-delete it, which
isn't what you would expect. The compute init code already handles
the case of soft-deleted instances while it was down, so we just
need to alter the frontend behavior.

Note that tests for this are added in the next patch, which was
written first and because there would be a ton of conflicts
generated by inserting them here.

Change-Id: I09f33bbcd7799b2bc1289b6100b291a7e6b26d9c

commit_message:
one global-requirements.txt to rule them all

... and in the darkness bind them.

This moves the contents of requirements.txt and
test-requirements.txt to a single file, global-requirements.txt.
This means that regardless of whether a requirement is in
either file it will get checked. This massively simplifies the
checking and upgrading of req and test-req files.

This also adds in a unit testing framework for the update.py
script to ensure it does what we think it does. This is
accomplished by making a fake tree with a set of req and test-req
files, running update.py, and ensuring the updates were made
that we expected. It includes testing for the oslo url case,
as well as test-requires.

is missing, the server will return 500 internal error or 409 conflict

Fixes: Bug 1136342
'}]
commit_message:
V3 API need to check mandatory field when creating resources

When creating items like project, role through V3 API, if name field
is missing, the server will return 500 internal error or 409 conflict
error, shall return 400 bad request error instead

Change-Id: I9deddcd4cf801306c16555b59bba7fdfab6556a7
Fixes: Bug 1136342

commit_message:
renames the stress test class to include the Volume keyword

tries to pick a better naming for the volume stress test class and
unifies stress test/class/file naming trying to serve as "guidance"
for future usage

commit_message:
Corrects the auth_token middleware configuration

Partially addresses LP 1207504

We need to ensure that auth_uri is set properly, that
auth_version defaults to v2.0, even when the v3 Keystone
API is available, and that the non-auth_uri config options
refer to the admin endpoint, not the service endpoint.

Change-Id: Ifbfbbf86bb6956b9b7c366dec5a8a12b383a476b

commit_message:
Fix dnsmasq package install failure

* added gettext to quantum_dhcp_build_packages, or it throws 'ERROR xgettext: Command not found'
* made dnsmasq_all to be installed last to fix install failure due to version dependency on dnsmasq-base(>= 2.65-1)
* added gettext to test example in dhcp_agent_spec.rb

Change-Id: I4f3f113d0b3cb182d52b0df763eb329d07a20166

commit_message:
Moved content shared with config guide to common directory.

Identified shared by the openstack-config guide and one or more other
guides and moved to the 'common' directory. Impacted href and fileref
values were also updated.

Guides involved were:

* openstack-compute-admin
* openstack-install
* openstack-config

Change-Id: I5074a65e925ebdaed7a8dff95619287c97be7562

commit_message:
Added Generic Persistence API and Datatypes

Added a generic persistence API for JobBoards,
Jobs, LogBooks, Workflows, FlowDetails, Tasks,
and TaskDetails. The currently implemented
backends are in-memory and sqlite db (by use
of sqlalchemy). Also implemented generic return
types (listed above) for the generic API.

Change-Id: I2e3c3d85c77276cc345242b75d6e116f5b892349

commit_message:
Update references with new Mailing List location

Yesterday, openstack@lists.launchpad.org was migrated with
all users to openstack@list.openstack.org.

This patch updates references to the old mailing list with the
new, to ensure that people encountering them don't accidentally
try and join the old list!

Change-Id: I0f8a91a361647a87fab9a1392d56a815f4d66eac

commit_message:
Return 201 (created) status response code in API POST actions.

The response code for API POST actions is 201 (created).
This fix intend to replicate the behaviour of the v3 api.

Fixes: bug #1199880

Change-Id: I9532dff1e48f111a0c6dd217eb72a7e6b9fdf80b

commit_message:
Modify local.py to not be dependent on Eventlet

Change local.py to use threading.local instead of being dependent on
Eventlet corolocal.local.

Change-Id: Ib544be1485823f6c619312fdee5a04031f48bbb4

commit_message:
Consolidate Xen Common Content

Previously:

* openstack-config/ch_computehypervisors.xml included common/introduction-to-xen.xml
* common/introduction-to-xen.xml included openstack-config/compute-configure-xen.xml
* openstack-config/compute-configure-xen.xml was not included
* directly from anywhere but common/introduction-to-xen.xml

This patch moves openstack-config/compute-configure-xen.xml and updates the relevant
xi:include, I also renamed the Xen files involved in the process to have
xen as the suffix.

Change-Id: I1b0e1809e26673104a53641476479fa48321abd6

There is no content to that blueprint where there should be some rationale and discussion of the way the feature should operate and ideally why it is desirable.

This implementation is pretty brute force and configures and enables apache modules without even checking if APACHE_ENABLED_SERVICES has any services enabled.  It needs to also take in to account any interactions with Horizon requirements and potential overlap with https://blueprints.launchpad.net/devstack/+spec/devstack-setup-apache-keystone.'}, {'account_id': 4108, 'date': '2013-06-21 19:50:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: No score

@Dean 

I can shed some light as for the rationale and the way the feature should operate. 

This work is aligned with work done in Swift for Greezly to enable full fledged Apache2 front end to Swift as alternative to the use of a python minimalistic web front end.

Through the work proposed here, devstack users can use this new Swift feature.

Also, through this work, it would become possible to build test VMs to perform functional testing of new patches to the Swift source code tree with an Apache2 web front end, identifying any issues arising from such a patch. The need for such tests came up recently as code was merged twice which broke the Apache2 support.

We have merged Swift template files this week to enable Devstack to use them.  

I hope this clarifies things.'}, {'account_id': 2649, 'date': '2013-06-22 06:01:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 2649, 'date': '2013-06-22 06:25:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Dean,  this patch is to enable for apache and wsgi module as front end for swift services. it also consider to add more support for other services such as keystone as you mentioned. 

The function 'is_apache_enabled_service' will detect environment variable APACHE_ENABLED_SERVICES+=swift,keystone if apache is used for some of the services. Currently swift already support it with apache and wsgi template files. 

This patch won't touch Horizon configuration. Their vhost and wsgi files are different and coexist in apache server."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-06-22 06:52:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Doesn't seem to work

I take my working default setup including swift, add APACHE_ENABLED_SERVICES=swift to it and swift is no longer functional.  stack.sh fails trying to upload the cirros image to glance/swift.  The log file is at http://aece4daa230f35e74492-39fdf687387aa3592f5ac8ce0686d07c.r96.cf2.rackcdn.com/stack.sh.log.2013-07-01-200957 if you want to dig in to it, I have something for $DAY_JOB to finish before the holiday.'}, {'account_id': 2649, 'date': '2013-07-03 06:33:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 2649, 'date': '2013-07-03 06:47:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

@Dean, based on your log, I find the reason of glance internal error. It is caused by the failure of restarting apache server due to the old ownership of /var/lock/apache2 directory (www-data by default). When running apache server as STACK_USER(dtroyer), this lock dir need to be also owned by this user. Otherwise it will fail the script to start apache server which hosts swift servers. I have added chown command before starting apache server to solve this problem.

Here're 3 line of log I found this problem:
------------------------------------
2013-07-01 20:14:29  * Starting web server apache2
2013-07-01 20:14:29 /var/lock/apache2 already exists but is not a directory owned by dtroyer.
2013-07-01 20:14:29 Please fix manually. Aborting."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-03 07:21:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Works for me

Build succeeded.

commit_message:
enable apache2 server as front end for swift

1.install apache and wsgi module
2.config apache2 vhost and wsgi files for proxy,
account, container and object server.
3.refactor apache functions from horizon and swift
into lib/apache

Change-Id: I3a5d1e511c5dca1e6d01a1adca8fda0a43d4f632
Implements: blueprint enable-apache-frontend-for-swift

This change syncs message catalogs with grizzly code changes, so it's appropriate for stable.
I'm just not sure how to verify this, is there a unittest in Horizon verifying message catalogs?"}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2013-08-01 20:10:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

There is no specific unit tests to check I18N strings in Horizon.

We check the message catalogs are valid indirectly.

Both of PO update and MO update are done by Django tools (makemessages and compilemessages). makemessages updates PO files by extracting translatable strings from the codes, and MO files are generated by compiling PO files. In the compilation processing, PO file format check is done.
It ensures the message catalogs are valid.

In addition, English message catalog (more precisely MO file) is used in Horizon unit tests. If this catalog contains invalid formats or invalid strings, the unit tests should fail.'}, {'account_id': 1955, 'date': '2013-08-01 23:43:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Thanks for the explanation and it looks like we need to define guidelines for translatable messages in Horizon stable, as discussed in bug 1207442'}, {'account_id': 1420, 'date': '2013-08-02 03:50:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

commit_message:
Sync translation message catalogs with the latest code

In Grizzly branch several strings have been cleaned up since
the release. This commit update message catalog based on the
current code. This allows translators to use the latest ones
and it is good to sync them with the code before the release.

Fixes bug #1207442

Note that this patch is directly posted since message strings
in master are different and will be updated at different timing.

Change-Id: I53cfb5be2f791f5e446fba5a838fd2512d994146

in Oslo.

commit_message:
fix compute_capabilities filter

this filter should not treat extra spec for pci_alias
as capabilities.

Signed-off-by: Yongli He <yongli.he@intel.com>

Change-Id: I5cbc47bb5e3cf40200f631c156d226ca1d034056

commit_message:
Make EvacuateTest DRYer

Each test in EvacuateTest creates request and application objects on its
own, so extract that to an isolated method to avoid code duplication.

blueprint nova-tests-code-duplication

Change-Id: Id0778b2cbb41edccd16820fa19de7951a7196f77

commit_message:
Add identity headers while calling glanceclient

Glance and glanceclient have patches up for a no auth
option in glance. In order for that to happen, nova needs to
send in additional information in its headers to glanceclient.
More details:
Some deployments have everything in the same network. And
for long running snapshots this may cause 401s because
token expires. In these cases the reauth is not required
cause nova has already authenticated the user.
This patch does not convert it to no auth. It only makes
it optional for glance users who do want to use that option.
Related patches:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/37062/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/36563/

Resolves bug 1200761

Change-Id: Ife02059abbdce7920f1f408b71e9745d777fa770

Resource definitions are meant to be stable; it doesn't feel right to me to be changing it temporarily."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2013-07-29 17:58:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Basically what Zane said. Our intent wasn't to make this compatible with the EC2 Instance even though we inherited that for convenience. We should move to have this resource match the Nova resource if nothing else. Suggest this resource be submitted as a separate compatibility resource registered under a different name."}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2013-07-29 18:53:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

+1 on the ImageName -> ImageId change.

-1 on the Flavor -> InstanceType change.

CloudServers' Flavor accepts a flavor ID (a number from 1 to 8), whereas Instance's InstanceType accepts a flavor name (eg. "m1.tiny").  Maybe now would be a good time to move away from AWS terminology and have both Instance and CloudServer use a "FlavorID" property? commit_message:
Rename rackspace server ImageName, Flavor, UserData.

Justifications for each rename are as follows:
- ImageName -> image: the Nova API uses imageRef, however heat does
  a lookup from image name to id, so 'image' covers either name or id.
- Flavor -> flavor: the Nova API uses flavorRef, but in the future heat
  should be able to do a lookup on the flavor name as well, so calling the
  attribute 'flavor' will API future-proof that change.
- UserData -> user_data: maps directly to Nova API

Change-Id: I1327f7b33d744908714dfb7a4caeb6ec306196e7

commit_message:
Fix extension hosts follow API v3 rules

* Add decorator expected_errors
* Rename parameter 'updates' to 'host' for update
* Add input validation
* Tidy up exception catching

Partially implements bp v3-api-extension-versioning

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ic7858460a1ebaf2e1981792b837e5858c7e9cccf

commit_message:
Ensure keystoneclient.auth_token is re-evaluated

Fixes bug 1207441

Force the re-evaluation of the keystoneclient.auth_token property
so as to avoid missing out on the in-built refresh logic when expiry
is imminent.

Change-Id: I8319e9e9a71e33e089fbe2fbc812d2b6c15da927

commit_message:
Sync DB models and migrations in keystone.assignment.backends.sql

This patch syncs models with migrations for:

-Domain
-GroupDomainGrant
-GroupProjectGrant
-Role
-UserDomainGrant
-UserProjectGrant

No actual schema change is taking place, this patch just corrects errors
in the model definitions.

partially implements bp db-sync-models-with-migrations

Change-Id: Ib3f22f56a9d00c725f21036ab4bfe4df5fad6876

commit_message:
Demote admin-passwd from core of API v3 as extensions os-admin-password

This patch move the action 'change_password' from core into extensions.
* Catch exception InstancePasswordSetFailed explicitly
* Add decorator 'expected_errors'
* Change naming style of action name and attributes
* Add testcase

Partially implements: bp v3-api-extension-versioning

DocImpact

Change-Id: I35fb73a47a58584ad6f8af78ffa087ecebde92a8

subject: Fix ambiguous exception class name for malformed EC2 IDs
messages:
[{'account_id': 6536, 'date': '2013-07-11 11:01:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5494, 'date': '2013-07-11 11:01:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

New patchset patch-id matches previous patchset, but commit message has changed.'}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2013-07-11 11:35:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hey Aswad,

take a look at the work being done in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/28330/10. The idea is to provide EC2 compliant error codes in the response, and your patch will not do that. 

In order to not perpetuate the wrong behaviour, what I suggest is to rebase on top of the patch above, provide the proper error codes as per EC2 spec, and wait until it lands (I think it's in pretty good shape ATM despite russellb's comments :))."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-11 11:54:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Doesn't seem to work

commit_message:
Fix ambiguous exception class name for malformed EC2 IDs

* InvalidInstanceIDMalformed exception was raised for both - malformed instance id and volume id.
* This fix renames the exception class to InvalidEC2IDMalformed makes the error message more generic.
* Fixes bug#1199308

Change-Id: I09771275468e6b249200bae09bb15af16b298d77

"}, {'account_id': 1082, 'date': '2013-04-29 18:01:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I don't think that nova should treat a "root volume" special in any way.  I can think of a number of cases where detaching something that nova might think is a "root volume".

Imagine booting from a volume (even possibly a cdrom presented as a volume), attaching another volume, installing to the second volume and then detaching the original root.

Basically, the concept of "root volume" is extremely simplistic.

I think a better way to handle this desire would be to add an API call to tag a volume as "undetachable".  This follows convention other places such as:
 * chmod -w do-not-delete.txt
 * "termination protection" (not sure if nova has this or not) http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/Using_ChangingDisableAPITermination.html'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-04-29 21:11:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Scott's concerns aside, this needs a unit test."}, {'account_id': 6896, 'date': '2013-04-30 09:19:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Good point, the design needs a bit more thinking.'}, {'account_id': 6896, 'date': '2013-05-01 13:11:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Why not have the default as not-detachable and have a --force option to detach when needed?'}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2013-05-01 14:01:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Scott - The description and logic are to prevent detachment of the boot device, not root volume - i.e. the device that the VM is currently booted from.

Even in the case of booting from a CD and installing to another volume my understanding is that the VM would need to reboot before it uses that new volume, at which point it becomes the (non detachable) boot device.'}, {'account_id': 1082, 'date': '2013-05-02 01:52:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Phil,
  If a vm reboots with 2 volumes attached, it doesn't change nova's view of what was the "boot volume" in any way that I'm aware of.
  My basic argument, though is that nova shouldn't bother attempting to know or care that a volume is attached.  Nova has no real way of knowing if the OS considers any block device to be "in use".  I could be missing something, but to my knowledge, there is no way for the OS to tell the hardware that a block device is "in use".  Maybe there is, and if thats the case, and it passes through kvm such that nova can "know" about it, then I retract my argument.

  For a very simplistic case, consider booting cirros from a volume.  One supported method of doing so would use the grub on the volume to load the kernel and initramfs, but would then run entirely from ram.  At that point a 'detach' of the volume is perfectly reasonable.  I've done similar tricks in the past where I boot an image, kexec into an initramfs and start wiping the initial boot volume.
I'd be annoyed if nova refused such a detach request, and especially if it insisted that it wouldn't let me.
  Thats why I suggested adding a "protect" flag.  Then, I can opt in to protecting my volumes from detach (or even delete).  Then, my accidental "detach device" would be met with a "Sorry, This device is protected from detaching".

  I do respect that you're just trying to protect your users from doing stupid things, but I just think its at the wrong level.'}, {'account_id': 6896, 'date': '2013-05-09 19:00:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 6896, 'date': '2013-05-09 19:04:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

This patchset is sent just for the sake of completeness. This adds a test case and fixes existing unit tests. I haven't addressed the design concerns raised in patchset 1 yet."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-05-09 19:47:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

Build succeeded.

This patch prevents a volume being detached when it is being
used as a boot-device and the instance is not deleted

commit_message:
This patchset improves py3k support for hacking

A few small changes:
- py3-style printing
- py3-style exception catching (, -> as)
- handle title as decoded string, not as bytes
- handle import configparser change
- handle gettext.install call change

Change-Id: I511a2176e7b351aee69c9e39cb0631bd8438f035

So this needs to be rewritten as per the comments on the corresponding glance change Ib9878680867af77cedaf92c54c1564cd388857a7

Some notes:

As for the glance case, no config should be needed here as the images in the _base dir should only be read from and so there should be no knock on affect from later allocations due to writes.

This will be largely redundant processing in the case of qcow images for example. Do we want to restrict to raw only?

A related issue is the transfer of these large raw images across the network. Perhaps it would be good to support the tar format or something to transfer, so that holes are sparsified in the transfer too. Something for future thought."}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2013-07-25 05:08:46.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-25 06:08:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Works for me

3) This is a feature, not a bug IMO, which means it should be a blueprint'}, {'account_id': 1812, 'date': '2013-07-25 18:45:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

I wouldn't say this was a feature.
It's just more efficient processing of existing data.
Also this is independent of glance I think.

Now there may be other reasons to reconsider this patch.

1. It does redundant processing of already sparse images like qcow files

2. There is no thought given to efficiency of network transport

You could handle both by storing tar files in glance for example and having nova extract the tar efficiently.
Actually forget tar, qcow could be leveraged for this.

Now users can use qcow to get these efficiencies.
qcow is stored and transferred efficiently and
converted to sparse raw by nova already.

Even if glance was given raw images, one might auto convert to qcow2 within glance to get these efficiencies automatically. One could tag such qcow images I suppose
so that nova would convert to sparse raw or leave as qcow as appropriate."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-07-26 01:49:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

Thanks for the corrections, pbrady.  I obviously didn't look at this close enough before leaving my review."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-02 06:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

subject: Unfubar "unfubar_setuptools"
messages:
[{'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2013-08-01 04:32:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I saw [1] go by but was never merged.  I still don't understand what "The current state of setuptools upgrading is a giant giant giant mess
perpetrated on the masses by the lord of evil. Conflicting versions of
things can wind up on the system and then everything breaks." means.  

Can we please have less histrionics and just a technical description of why these work-arounds are needed?  I'm guessing this is an Ubuntu issue?

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/38040/'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-01 05:21:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- http://logs.openstack.org/28/39628/1/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-full/1363159 : SUCCESS in 44m 21s
- http://logs.openstack.org/28/39628/1/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-cells-full/83a04c5 : FAILURE in 33m 05s (non-voting)
- http://logs.openstack.org/28/39628/1/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-testr-full/a9697e6 : SUCCESS in 29m 46s (non-voting)
- http://logs.openstack.org/28/39628/1/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-postgres-full/4a06d28 : SUCCESS in 55m 48s
- http://logs.openstack.org/28/39628/1/check/gate-tempest-devstack-vm-neutron/3aa82df : FAILURE in 7m 59s (non-voting)
- http://logs.openstack.org/28/39628/1/check/gate-grenade-devstack-vm/dae9880 : SUCCESS in 21m 53s
'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2013-08-01 07:07:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Do not merge

This is a Python/pip issue related to proper dependency installation that is best solved by trashing all distro's setuptools and pip installations and replacing them with known working current releases.  It is less of a problem on Ubuntu due to fewer unexpected changes made in the python-pip package; fedora tries to straddle the fence (by having symlinks pip-python and python-pip pointing to /usr/bin/pip) and would have been fine if not for the RHEL6 work-around get_pip_command() that only looked for is_fedora() rather than just RHEL6 where that particular problem lies.

One thing that will happen is the need for some of the RHEL6 work-arounds will go away once a modern setuptools and pip are in place, though it will probably take more hackery to get to that point.  The initial need was to make Ubuntu work for some specific gate issues."}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2013-08-01 09:39:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I don't think so; I believe the "install, remove distro package, install" has an issue on RHEL (and Fedora, I think) that pip installs to /usr/lib by default (not /usr/local as probably happens on Ubuntu?)

So the first install overwrites the package version, the removal of the distro package deletes it, and the third install can't continue.  I tried it [1] and unfortunately it doesn't even get that far; i guess the setuptools installation overwrites something so the install of pip doesn't work anyway

[1] http://pastebin.com/jHsbzgNM'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2013-08-02 05:46:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

This was not meant to be merged; see [1] for follow-on change

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/39862/'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-01 04:25:42.000000000', 'message': 'Unfubar "unfubar_setuptools"

Change 0392a10a635a8befb13ff242e2ed5d5be4b23560 apparently introduced
this as "Unbreak the giant mess that is the current state of
setuptools" without explaination of what that giant mess actually is.

get_pip_command assumes pip is called "pip-python" on Fedora based
distros because we are using the packaged pip.  Thus after this code
re-installs upstream pip, which is not renamed, further progress
halts.

I doubt this is the correct solution, but without a better
explaination of the reasoning behind the change it's hard to
understand what is trying to be achieved.

Change-Id: I0b85b2dde1bf4e1f2de71a5c1e7cbd34b6b06e27
'}]
commit_message:
Unfubar "unfubar_setuptools"

Change 0392a10a635a8befb13ff242e2ed5d5be4b23560 apparently introduced
this as "Unbreak the giant mess that is the current state of
setuptools" without explaination of what that giant mess actually is.

get_pip_command assumes pip is called "pip-python" on Fedora based
distros because we are using the packaged pip.  Thus after this code
re-installs upstream pip, which is not renamed, further progress
halts.

I doubt this is the correct solution, but without a better
explaination of the reasoning behind the change it's hard to
understand what is trying to be achieved.

Change-Id: I0b85b2dde1bf4e1f2de71a5c1e7cbd34b6b06e27

commit_message:
Port ips-extended to API-v3 ips core API Part 2

This includes on ips responses extended ip information: mac address and type,
adds V3 version of the views and the tests to also test this information, which
affects servers and ips core API.

related to bp nova-v3-api

Change-Id: I699f6e27b53663f358b63615e7dd0f1627c4730b

commit_message:
NoSuchOptError should be used not AttributeError

Switch back to previous behavior. Looks like we are missing a test to
enforce the old behavior that everyone depends on

Fixes LP# 1207541

commit_message:
Add index to reservations.uuid column

Committing or rolling back reservations gets slow once a large number of
reservations have built up in the db.  Since they're being queried by
uuid this adds an index to speed up that operation.

Note that this can be slow with a large number of rows.

bug 1203872

Change-Id: Ida503206194a567a5c6811a304154d067c5faa83

commit_message:
Add command for listing available service providers

implements blueprint service-types-cli

Add command service-provider-list - lists service providers available
in neutron configuration

Change-Id: I2ea25abc6d54b93fd9d11e8c494d7e3f77f25c53

commit_message:
Update references with new Mailing List location

Yesterday, openstack@lists.launchpad.org was migrated with
all users to openstack@list.openstack.org.

This patch updates references to the old mailing list with the
new, to ensure that people encountering them don't accidentally
try and join the old list!

Change-Id: Ica89d0f9347cd7ee1d906acb8ef8949a6d39316b

The last line of "Total Compute Node Failure" section in "Maintenance,
Failures, and Debugging" chapter refers to "After a compute node Reboots"
for the detail of volume re-attaching. However, volume re-attaching is
described in "Volumes" section instead of "After a compute node Reboots".

This commit also fixes typo in ch_arch_network_design.xml.

Change-Id: Icc225369f9f7c9f41da74766478e40b3cf984891
'}]
commit_message:
Fix the section reference in ch_ops_maintenance

The last line of "Total Compute Node Failure" section in "Maintenance,
Failures, and Debugging" chapter refers to "After a compute node Reboots"
for the detail of volume re-attaching. However, volume re-attaching is
described in "Volumes" section instead of "After a compute node Reboots".

This commit also fixes typo in ch_arch_network_design.xml.

Change-Id: Icc225369f9f7c9f41da74766478e40b3cf984891

commit_message:
Adds NoAuthMiddleware for V3

Adds a V3 version of NoAuthMiddleware which returns a url which
unlike the V2 version does not include the tenant_id in the url.

Also fixes bug with the V2 version where it would create broken
urls on Windows because os.path.join was used

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-remove-project-id

DocImpact

Change-Id: I7ecffea52c3662344ac694997bb08a16506abbbd

commit_message:
Allow the Ceilometer Alarm to be used with cfn-push-stats

This is for when:
- Ceilometer does not support the desired custom metric
- Easier migration to Ceilometer Alarms (reuse most of old templates)

A watchrule is create within the Ceilometer alarm, but it is marked
as belonging to Ceilometer. This is used in the follow situation:
- So we can figure out that we don't need to run the watch periodic task
- when we receive new sample data we can forward the data to Ceilometer

blueprint watch-ceilometer
Change-Id: I0d672e69a522a23158805d75378f4bfe631b4bf3

I'm trying to think of a reason that AWS::AutoScaling::AutoScalingGroup would need the tags but OS::Heat::InstanceGroup would not. Assuming this was inadvertent, I think that we should add the extra tag to the list just before we insert it in the template, in _make_instance().

In any event, we should *not* modify the state of self.properties.data (in fact, we should never touch .data at all - the existing code is wrong there) on the fly, because this state will not be stored in the database (one of many reasons why modifying state is evil). So the tags will be present after a create() or update(), but not for the servers created during a scaling event."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-31 12:39:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

(4 inline comments)

This looks better thanks. There is one issue addressed inline that could be considered stylistic, but I'm -1ing because there is some behaviour that is definitely not intentional and could be considered a bug.

In general, I'm persuaded by the arguments of the functional programming school that the output of a function should only depend on its inputs (self counts) and that a function should not modify any external state. (In practice this means that a function takes data as an input and returns a _copy_ of the data that has then been modified.) They go far too far, of course, because at the end of the day we have to get actual work done, and that means modifying state (afaict the hoops you have to jump through to, say, print something in e.g. Haskell are absurd). But to the extent that code is just rearranging data in data structures (like here), I've found this to be a very, very useful design heuristic.

In a language like C with manual memory management there are strong disincentives to doing this, but in a reference-counted, garbage-collected language like Python there are no such downsides. Writing code that does not make use of external state makes it much easier to test and avoids problems like this one (where you get the wrong answer if you call it multiple times)."}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-08-01 10:51:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-01 11:43:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

commit_message:
Fixes for v3 API servers tests

Fixes some v3 API servers unittests to correctly use the
fake v3 wsgi_app rather than the v2 one. Also fixes
xml in test_update_server_invalid_xml_raises_lookup so
that it will only cause a LookupError rather than a LookupError
and an ExpatError as the latter will mask the failure of the former
to be raised.

Also adds checking of the actual error message returned for the two
unittests affected.

partially implements blueprint v3-api-unittests

Change-Id: I2abf8875e2cc3feda14f93d8c1e7a88c5a278ca8

commit_message:
use 'exc_info=True' instead of import traceback

We need log traceback message sometime, but people who ignore 'exc_info'
argument would import traceback for getting traceback message. This work
is already done by 'exc_info' in logging module. For example:

logger.error('msg', exc_info=True)
                                  # exc_info evaluate as true and log
                                      message from sys.exc_info()
logger.debug('msg', exc_info=(type, value, traceback))
                                  # exc_info evaluate as an exception
                                    tuple and log message from this
                                    tuple
logger.exception('msg')
                                  # exception add exc_info=1 automatically

Change-Id: I9e1caf05fcf06bb977597076ebe278b593d70bf4

commit_message:
Add support for Neutron https endpoint

This patch adds a parameter to specify Neutronclient ca certificate file
location to support Neutron https endpoint.

Fix bug #1206330

Change-Id: I9ecdd24cf0efcb5ef895e529e516d248214592c1

[{'created': '2013-07-29 21:28:03.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes Hyper-V issues on versions prior to 2012

Fixes bug: #1203059

Hyper-V 2012 introduced live migration support and a WMI namespace that
can be used to handle iSCSI targets.

The Hyper-V driver was not properly recognizing versions of the os prior to
2012 causing an exception during startup due to the usage of unsupported
features.

Unit tests have been added to test the behaviour of the driver with
different os versions.

Change-Id: I88056a2e89552b94513ba1ead046dfda57567815
'}]
commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V issues on versions prior to 2012

Fixes bug: #1203059

Hyper-V 2012 introduced live migration support and a WMI namespace that
can be used to handle iSCSI targets.

The Hyper-V driver was not properly recognizing versions of the os prior to
2012 causing an exception during startup due to the usage of unsupported
features.

Unit tests have been added to test the behaviour of the driver with
different os versions.

Change-Id: I88056a2e89552b94513ba1ead046dfda57567815

Call cfn-create-aws-symlinks in rackspace servers.

This will also be required for arch, gentoo and opensuse
when the pip install prefix is known.

commit_message:
Stop delete polling after status == DELETED.

A rackspace server can be in status DELETED for some minutes
until a 404 is raised. This change speeds the deletion of a stack
by considering the resource deleted as soon as the status changes
to DELETED.

Change-Id: Id81d3099ef6b41b374973074b065b20c2acc9667

Bug 1190364

get_instance_disk_info() now takes an additional, optional argument
of block_device_info. When passed in, we use it to filter out
volumes, such that they are not returned. Previously, any devices
classified as "file" as parsed from the instance XML were considered
local disks. This assumption is incorrect, since some volumes are
simply files, rather than block devices.

Added a new test, based almost entirely off the existing test case
for this function, which represents an XML file with two fake
file-based (NFS-like) volumes and associated block_device_info to
claim those volumes.

Change-Id: I4809a8fd68eb0f709347aa7cad0fa85389ade41c
(cherry picked from commit e71081b856b06513cc1e56a9adb2a619967f0eae)
'}]
commit_message:
Fix resizes with attached file-based volumes

Bug 1190364

get_instance_disk_info() now takes an additional, optional argument
of block_device_info. When passed in, we use it to filter out
volumes, such that they are not returned. Previously, any devices
classified as "file" as parsed from the instance XML were considered
local disks. This assumption is incorrect, since some volumes are
simply files, rather than block devices.

Added a new test, based almost entirely off the existing test case
for this function, which represents an XML file with two fake
file-based (NFS-like) volumes and associated block_device_info to
claim those volumes.

Change-Id: I4809a8fd68eb0f709347aa7cad0fa85389ade41c
(cherry picked from commit e71081b856b06513cc1e56a9adb2a619967f0eae)

commit_message:
Copy tempest.log to logs dir after tempest run

Devstack change I91f2ee781c4a7a18c561ea3e3b26832b97431464 configures
tempest to print all log messages into a tempest.log file located in
the tempest repo that gets cloned as part of devstack. This commit
copies the log file into log directory so that it will get uploaded
to the log server with the other logs.

Change-Id: I45e01c87547c65725d25d8d338c983ce9297bf20

commit_message:
Use the same logic everywhere for requirements files

Currently, the environment variable isn't always respected, especially when
dealing with the egg_info command. Let's factorize the code into a function
and use it everywhere instead of the REQUIREMENTS_FILES variable.

Change-Id: I1c3224ef76ee724c8176eb00ef948d80259e3c17

[{'created': '2013-07-31 18:06:53.000000000', 'message': 'Remove repeated initialisation

Due to the mox object being created twice, anything that was mocked
by the original instance only will never be unset. Remove the repeated
self.mox creation to allow new tests to run properly.

Change-Id: Icf644178f5a8270f913997e7e3f10dade412b321
'}]
commit_message:
Remove repeated initialisation

Due to the mox object being created twice, anything that was mocked
by the original instance only will never be unset. Remove the repeated
self.mox creation to allow new tests to run properly.

Change-Id: Icf644178f5a8270f913997e7e3f10dade412b321

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-02 01:09:02.000000000', 'message': 'Update allowed_hosts conditional statement

In the origin quantum::db::mysql, if the value of $allowed_hosts
contains or equals to $host, then puppet will complain duplicate
declaration error. This patch is aim to update the allowed_hosts
conditonal statement in quantum::db::mysql.

There are two cases to pass $allowed_hosts to $real_allowed_hosts:

   - If $allowed_hosts is array,then remove $host from $allowed_hosts;
   - elsif $allowed_hosts is string and not equivalent to $host;

At last, if $real_allowed_hosts is not undef, then run
quantum::db::mysql::host_access

Fix bug 1206444

Change-Id: I4c7aef5b7c002c799e8c78fc45dfc3362d41d6ee
'}]
commit_message:
Update allowed_hosts conditional statement

In the origin quantum::db::mysql, if the value of $allowed_hosts
contains or equals to $host, then puppet will complain duplicate
declaration error. This patch is aim to update the allowed_hosts
conditonal statement in quantum::db::mysql.

There are two cases to pass $allowed_hosts to $real_allowed_hosts:

   - If $allowed_hosts is array,then remove $host from $allowed_hosts;
   - elsif $allowed_hosts is string and not equivalent to $host;

At last, if $real_allowed_hosts is not undef, then run
quantum::db::mysql::host_access

Fix bug 1206444

Change-Id: I4c7aef5b7c002c799e8c78fc45dfc3362d41d6ee

[{'created': '2013-07-19 00:57:11.000000000', 'message': "More normal assignment and identity dependencies

The assignment and identity backends have a circular dependency,
and the dependency code didn't handle it so the assignment and
identity backends were different than the rest.

This change makes it so that the dependency code handles circular
dependencies and cleans up the assignment and identity backends
to use the normal dependency code like the other backends.

Change-Id: I8716a65b984c26fcaaf2595463db09e1f02cb475

commit_message:
Use dependency injection for assignment and identity

The assignment and identity backends don't use normal
dependency injection because of a circular reference.

Support for circular references was added, so these
backends can now use normal dependency injection.

Fixes: bug 1200769
Fixes: bug 1204605

Change-Id: I8716a65b984c26fcaaf2595463db09e1f02cb475

subject: Handle circular dependencies

commit_message:
Handle circular dependencies

The dependency injection code doesn't handle circular
dependencies. This change makes it so that the
dependency injection code allows circular dependencies.

Part of fix for bug 1204605

Change-Id: I8de166a352ac727c7ddf27bae420b7c7ab22415f

commit_message:
Clear out the dependency registry between tests

As part of the process during several tests setUp
where the backends are reloaded, automatic dependency
injection takes place. The REGISTRY is being updated
with new providers and it's also looking up the
required dependencies. Some of the providers for the
requirements may not have been updated yet with the
new provider object, so it loads an object that
was created from a previous test run rather than the
current one. This can cause tests to
fail when one class gets a ref to the old one
(it depends on the order that the tests are run).

This change clears out the registry of providers before
loading backends. It only affects testing.

Part of fix for bug 1204605

Change-Id: Ib845493fa13531225e4be7e3b6cc315b9d19a0f4
